# Jose’s Ideas:

We could make a match-3 game with RPG elements. Fantasy-Themed, cute graphics (perhaps a bunch of simple vectors for iconography and pixelated stuff).

A match-three Puzzle game, inspired by Puzzles and Dragons or maybe Candy Crush.

Built with React, React, Typescript, Jotai and Zustand.

## Views:

- Start Screen
- Maybe Load and Save screens?
- Map Screen ala Mario 3 or Pokemon
- Battle View (the one with the Match-3 board)
- Game Over
- Item Stop
- Modals
  - Credits
  - Settings (mostly Volume control for audio effects and music)

## Similar Games:

- Puzzles and Dragons: similar core gameplay
- I really like the vibes and fonts used in Stardew Valley and fields of mistria. The font for katana zero is also great
- The Map for Pokemon / Super Mario World

## RPG Elements:

The characters and enemies could have some rudimentary stats like:

- Power (POW) for the potency of their actions (both sides could use the same formulas)
- Vitality (VIT)
  - Effects:
  - Characters: increase their contribution to the Party’s HP pool
  - Enemy: Determines their HP
- Speed (SPD)
  - Effects:
  - Enemy: Determines their attack intervals
  - Characters: Increase how much their Skill Cooldown Bar fills each second (or maybe changes its interval?)

We’d need to have functions in the /lib folder to calculate the cooldown and stuff like that, and calculate the party’s collective HP, plus all the normal RPG stuff like Damage Calculation.

The Level-Up System could work like it does in SMT:

- Automatic Stat Growth
- Max Level: 40 (?)
- You get 1 point you can freely assign per level
- This is really easy to calculate if we increase each stat by a given amount each level.
  - This also allows us to implement decreasing marginal returns on investment (ROI) on points. Dark Souls and Elden Ring do something similar with levels.
  - E.g. Warriors get 4 VIT points per level until level 10, then 3 VIT points per level up to level 20, then 2 up to level 30…

Additionally, characters must have:

* UltimateFlatDamageBonus (para darle al arquero/Rogue)
* BaselineDamageMultiplier (so we can set it to \-1 for the healer)
* ActionTarget (enemy or ally, this way we can implement healer allies and enemies)

## Characters:

The characters will be color-coded.

* Warrior:
  * Color: Blue?
  * Stats: Mid power, mid speed, high VIT
  * The party’s main Tank, and a decent, reliable damage dealer.
* Rogue:
  * Color: Green
  * His ultimate could have a *flat Damage Bonus* to make up for his low Power state
  * Stats: Low Power, high speed, mid VIT.
* Mage:
  * Color: Purple? Pink?
  * Stats: High power, low speed, low VIT
* Healer:
  * Color: Yellow? White but the white orb is anti-flash white and has very-light-details?
  * Stats: Balanced but low stats overall

## Why color-code characters and orbs:

* It makes the UI more intuitive
* It adds a strategic aspect to the gameplay and another use for consumables
  * It forces the player to prioritize which orbs to swipe.
  * When not enough orbs of a given color are available (e.g. not enough Green orbs to trigger strong heals from the Healer), the player could use a consumable to clear the board or a given row in order to free up space for their desired orbs to maybe show up.

## BattleView functionality Proposal:

The Enemy and its health bar.

The Party with its health bar (let’s make a collective health pool for now) and each of them with its Skill Cooldown Bar (maybe you can think of a better name).

The Characters could be Color-Coded to match the Orbs you match in the Board.

Each Character has an Action (the warrior attacks, the healer heals…)

The “Game Board” is where you play the Match-Three puzzle where you match Orbs.

When you match the orb with the Character’s color, it will perform its action.

If you match more than 3 orbs, you get a multiplier. The multiplier makes your actions more powerful (could be like x1 for 3, and all the way up to x2 for 6 orbs).

Combination of enemies attacking in set time-intervals based on their stats and your limited HP pool would essentially work as a roundabout way to implement a timer, creating a fast-paced “Nuke the Enemy before they nuke you” type of situation, and forcing you use your healer to regain valuable seconds. It also encourages abusing Ultimate Skills.

## Item Store:

An item store where you can buy special consumables you can use in Battle.

We could add an additional, highlighted slot to the store: Special Offer. Basically, one randomly-selected item from the shop can be purchased once per stage/world at something like 50% of the original price.

## Dungeons and Maps:

A Dungeon you can grind a bit on.

Maybe we could have a short Map like Candy Crush’s It could be hard-coded, programmed with only two variables “stage” and “world” (kinda like it works in Mario), with some “stages” being bosses. Each “world” is a different component.

All Stage nodes in the map receive basic props (currentStage, an Object with every party member’s Character Stats called PartyStats or something, and the Inventory).

## Technical (General):

- The multiplier could be calculated like:
  - matchedPos \= getMatchedPositions()
  - multiplier= getDmgMultiplier(matchedPos.length)
- The entire BattleView needs to be Jotai-based so we don’t need to trigger unnecessary re-renders and so we don’t need to prop drill, and so we can trigger animations globally.
- BattleView should receive the game’s state as props, so it doesn’t accidentally cause side-effects, and so we don’t rely on Zustand.
- The rest of the game needs to be really really consistent so we should probably use a Zustand Store for most things.
  - The Store, Start Menu, etc are not super expensive rendering-wise so we could use Immer, which makes Zustand really nice to use and keeps state consistent.
- In order to calculate combos and other stuff, we will for sure need to save the previous state of the board as well as the current one.
  - This would be a Stack
  - We’ll probably need to write functions in the /lib directory to do the heavy lifting and test them with Vitest when they’re tricky. Those tests double as a benchmark for execution speed.
- In order to trigger animations globally like View Transitions, we’ll need an ever-present “GlobalAnimationsOverlay” component.
  - We just need to create an  nullable Atom and create an ever-present component that triggers an animation once based on the value of the atom (and does nothing when the atom is set to null)
- Some component libraries like 8bitcn would help: https://www.8bitcn.com/

## Technical (Save Management) \- Proposal:

* It might be easier to store save-data in an atom, containing an array of 3 nullable SaveData objects, which would be composed of a bunch of different data stored in the Zustand Store.
* That data only needs to be handled by the Save Game and Load Game views.
* SaveData is a highly complex data type and we’ll probably have to put it together in its own file in the /types folder by combining a bunch of other types used throughout the game.
* We’ll need a LoadSaveData method in the Zustand store, to set all the store parameters from the SaveData Object.
